WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.240
Hi everyone, I'm Ahmadou Dicko and I want to talk to you today about Humanitarian Data

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:17.360
Science with R, particularly how to build reproducible humanitarian reports.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:21.680
I found this topic really relevant today because of the rise in the number of crises all around

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:28.879
the world due to disasters, conflict, epidemics and so on.

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:33.799
And you have places in crisis for decades.

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:39.520
What you can see in this picture is a camp of displaced people in the Central African

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:40.520
Republic.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:43.680
Central African Republic is a good example.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:50.919
In this country of 4.7 million people, one out of four people are currently displaced

00:00:50.919 --> 00:00:55.040
due to a crisis that lasted more than 10 years.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:00.040
Half of the population are currently food insecure.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:03.480
It's a lot and there's a lot of people in need.

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.959
And as you can expect, a lot of organizations are on the ground trying to help.

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:16.040
But at the same time, in Central African Republic, there's also a lot of incidents and attacks

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:19.599
targeting humanitarians.

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:25.760
Just last year, more than 300 incidents were recorded, affecting mostly humanitarians.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:26.760
And it's a lot.

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:31.519
I think it's really one of the hardest places to work for a humanitarian worker.

00:01:31.519 --> 00:01:38.360
So people out there are really doing a great job and it's not really easy.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:39.360
But how do I know all of this?

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:43.879
How do I know all these numbers, all these figures?

00:01:43.879 --> 00:01:50.599
I can say it's because I care and I lived, for example, nearly 11 years in the center

00:01:50.599 --> 00:01:54.519
of Africa, not in this country, but really close.

00:01:54.519 --> 00:01:57.080
That's part of the reason.

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:59.839
I can also say that I'm working for a humanitarian organization.

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:02.279
It's also part of why I know this.

00:02:02.279 --> 00:02:07.519
But the real reason why I know all of this with all this precision is really because

00:02:07.519 --> 00:02:09.600
I'm reading reports.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:16.360
And these humanitarian reports are more and more analytical and data-driven and can be

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:18.800
seen really as a data product.

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:24.440
So this humanitarian data product, I can share an example.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:30.199
For example, you can have this humanitarian situation document by OCHA, which is a humanitarian

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:33.559
organization in Central African Republic.

00:02:33.559 --> 00:02:36.600
They have a really great team doing an amazing job there.

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:42.960
And you can see, for example, in this document that 2.6 million people are currently in need.

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:49.199
And out of this 2.6, 1.8 million are targeted by organizations.

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:54.639
The targeting really can go deep and you can even see within the country how many people

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:00.520
are assisted and where you have more people assisted than in other places with the maps

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:01.520
that they are sharing.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:06.440
And this is really key information that are useful for people on the ground and also people

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:12.800
elsewhere like me that want to understand what's going on in this country.

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:17.639
And as you can see, this product is really well crafted and well designed.

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:19.300
And you can see a lot of data in there.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:23.479
So behind each data product, you have a data team.

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:29.160
And humanitarian data teams are as diverse as it can be.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:33.039
But we have some typical role in the team.

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:36.279
We can start with the analyst and let's call her Umu.

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:40.960
Our analyst, she's the one analyzing the data, creating tables and making visual.

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:48.880
She's also really in charge of anything related to the data, particularly tabular data.

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:53.160
And she's using Excel and Power BI to do that.

00:03:53.160 --> 00:04:00.080
And her colleague is a GIS officer and his name is Ali.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:08.039
And all special type of analysis, making maps and everything is usually his duty.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:12.800
And he's using QGIS and RGIS to do that.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:18.640
Now that you have really the core of the information we need, they cannot just be shared as it

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:19.640
is.

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:24.519
We need a designer, a graphical designer to really put all these documents together into

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:31.200
a single document, but also to look at the design of this table, of this chart and maps

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:33.100
and create also the type of infographics.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:35.640
So we have a graphic designer named Javier.

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:40.119
And Javier is really good using Adobe Illustrator and Adobe Design.

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:44.839
So they have really these tools that they master, they use very well.

00:04:44.839 --> 00:04:49.839
And it allows them to create document that's the one you just see.

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:53.760
But let's go maybe further and see how it works.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:05:00.799
So in a typical setting, Umo will get the raw data.

00:05:00.799 --> 00:05:07.119
She will crunch the data using Excel, Power BI and create some tables and some charts.

00:05:07.119 --> 00:05:13.160
At the same time, our GIS officer Ali will also do the same, will take special data and

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:15.720
create some maps.

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:22.720
Now that they have maps, tables and charts, this information will be shared with the designer.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:27.559
And he will be the one really combining all this information into a document.

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:30.920
And they can go back and forth until they're satisfied about the final product.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:36.079
And they can be shared now internally with other units in the organization or externally

00:05:36.079 --> 00:05:38.320
with other partners.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:41.920
Now what could go wrong with this setup?

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:44.660
Many things, but one thing that comes to my mind is with timeliness.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:53.299
So we want this document to be ready as soon as possible, because I think it's really life

00:05:53.299 --> 00:06:00.119
saving information and as soon as it can be validated and used, the better, right?

00:06:00.119 --> 00:06:05.980
But then if you share this product, let's say, okay, we have the draft we share with

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:11.100
external partners, NGOs, government or the UN organization, and they all have the input.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:16.260
The government can say, oh, the data is outdated and we have new version, you have to change

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:18.660
the data that you use to do that.

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:22.299
And maybe the NGOs or the UN organization can say, the methodology you use is good,

00:06:22.299 --> 00:06:27.899
but maybe I think this one is the one validated now and we have to change the approach.

00:06:27.899 --> 00:06:34.019
So all this change is more than just removing or fixing a typo on the document, you have

00:06:34.019 --> 00:06:37.940
to go back to the raw data and changing the whole document, right?

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:42.940
But then doing this, you have to keep track of what you did first.

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:45.980
And I think it's really key when you have to apply some change.

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:50.859
And when you are using point and click tools, it can be hard, not impossible, but really

00:06:50.859 --> 00:06:54.179
hard to track past changes applied to the data.

00:06:54.179 --> 00:06:58.019
And when you have a lot of really, because it's a process and you can go back and forth

00:06:58.019 --> 00:07:02.899
like that for many rounds, actually, and then it's easier to have some mistakes and not

00:07:02.899 --> 00:07:04.600
spot them.

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:12.920
So what we can ask now and is really the question is, is it possible to do better?

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:14.440
And the answer is yes.

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:20.519
And there are many approach maybe to just reduce the time we spend building this document

00:07:20.519 --> 00:07:30.559
and the time we spent really fixing this correction when we have a revision document.

00:07:30.559 --> 00:07:38.040
And if you look at the tools they are using, our analysis, mostly Excel and the GIS, and

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:42.160
the designer is mostly around the Adobe suite, that's fine.

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:47.279
But what we want to achieve is something that allow more transparency.

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:52.079
And one thing that going to mind is reproducibility.

00:07:52.079 --> 00:08:00.519
And one tool that allow us to have more reproducibility is R. R is a good choice, because you can

00:08:00.519 --> 00:08:02.839
because the ecosystem is really rich.

00:08:02.839 --> 00:08:10.519
We have a lot of packages to do analysis, maps, create beautiful tables and charts.

00:08:10.519 --> 00:08:16.239
And with R Markdown, we have one tool to create really any type of document and our designer

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:22.559
with his skills using, for example, CSS can create a really nice looking template, right?

00:08:22.559 --> 00:08:31.200
So we are pushing for a shift and let's see how the workflow will change.

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:38.479
Because now what we'll do is really to have a more R Markdown based workflow to have all

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:41.039
our reports.

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:45.400
Our reports used to be based on point and click tools, that's fine.

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:53.719
Now it will be really based on this R packages and our inputs will not be the input that

00:08:53.719 --> 00:08:58.119
we used to send to the designer, will not be the table, the charts and the map, but

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:02.080
the document will be a living document inside an R Markdown document.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:11.320
So the tidyverse will be used to crunch the data, to create some summary tables and output

00:09:11.599 --> 00:09:17.719
can be, for example, something from the GT flex table package or ggplot2 for any type

00:09:17.719 --> 00:09:18.719
of graphs.

00:09:18.719 --> 00:09:24.320
At the same time, any special data or type of information will be analyzed using the

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:28.760
SF package or the raster package and can be visualized using ggplot2 too.

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:33.880
But now all this analysis will live into one single R Markdown document, for example, in

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:34.880
this case.

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:40.599
And it brings a lot of transparency because we can all see what is in the document and

00:09:40.599 --> 00:09:46.440
it helps us also keep track of it because we can also use other nice tools like version

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:49.039
control that I don't want to mention too much.

00:09:49.039 --> 00:09:51.520
But there's a lot of goodies that come really with this approach.

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:56.960
And then we have our final document, when we are happy about our R Markdown document

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:03.119
that Javier provided with a nice template that he built.

00:10:03.359 --> 00:10:08.520
And then the final output for external users will be totally the same because with a template

00:10:08.520 --> 00:10:10.719
you can have a nice looking document.

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:18.080
They will not see any difference because for them it won't look really different.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:24.039
And that's really the key here because we don't want this document to be different because

00:10:24.039 --> 00:10:28.320
they are already looking really good but internally we can make this change.

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:35.159
Let's see how, for example, we take an example, how we can achieve something like that.

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:39.080
We take a really hypothetical example.

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:46.599
Let's say we want a one-pager on displacement, conflict-induced displacement, the number

00:10:46.599 --> 00:10:58.000
of conflicts per admin, admin one, and a situation of the funding situation in the country.

00:10:58.039 --> 00:11:02.400
So that's usually three types of information we need to do that, three or four.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:04.479
Let's see how we can achieve this.

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:07.200
First, we need some data.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:12.599
So for all this example, we will take data from a platform named HDX.

00:11:12.599 --> 00:11:20.359
HDX is one of the most used platforms by humanitarians to access data because all the data they are

00:11:20.359 --> 00:11:21.799
sharing also about the humanitarians.

00:11:21.799 --> 00:11:24.799
So you have really a lot of information.

00:11:24.799 --> 00:11:31.159
So Umu will go there, our analyst, and she will use the HDX package, which is really

00:11:31.159 --> 00:11:33.080
tidy-verse friendly.

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:38.479
And in three lines of code, she can search some data set, find the data set, and read

00:11:38.479 --> 00:11:39.479
it directly.

00:11:39.479 --> 00:11:44.880
So in four lines of code, you have access to the table that you want to use.

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:47.919
And now that we have the table, it's just easier to plug it to ggplot.

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:56.000
So in less than 10 lines of code, you have this conflict-induced displacement time series.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.760
And we can see, for example, in 2013, it was really worse here in the country in terms

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:04.960
of stock displacement due to conflict.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:10.960
Now we can use the flex-table package to create a table because Umu is not also just doing

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:14.559
chart but also table for the report.

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:18.840
And we use the same website to get information about requirements and funding.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:23.000
And this data set, for example, is updated on a daily basis.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.880
So the information is really up-to-date.

00:12:25.880 --> 00:12:29.520
And you have really access to key column.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:33.599
You can use the dplyr package to select the column you need and filter because we want

00:12:33.599 --> 00:12:36.320
just the past four years.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:37.799
And use the flex-table.

00:12:37.799 --> 00:12:40.880
And then in a few lines of code, again, we have our table.

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:46.880
So that's really a change in the way because just in a few lines of code, you have mostly

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:49.880
the product you need, right?

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:52.719
And we will do the same process for the map.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:13:00.799
Our GIS officer, Ali, will go to SGX and pull the data set he needs, read the data set,

00:13:00.799 --> 00:13:02.479
and put it into ggplot.

00:13:02.479 --> 00:13:08.719
And here we can see, for example, that it is not that difficult to access a shapefile

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:11.320
of the admin one level.

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:16.239
Now what can be more tricky is for him to access the conflict data and put it into the map.

00:13:16.239 --> 00:13:19.919
By default, on SGX, the conflict data is not spatial, right?

00:13:19.919 --> 00:13:22.880
But you have longitude and latitude columns.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:29.440
So what he will do, access the data from SGX, filter using dplyr the year that he wants,

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:39.239
and count the number of incidents by coordinates and just turn the data into a spatial data.

00:13:39.239 --> 00:13:45.479
So in a few lines of code, he is doing something that used to take really a lot of time and

00:13:45.479 --> 00:13:47.559
maybe need to involve a lot of tools.

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:50.640
Maybe one part will be done on Excel, another part on GS, and so on.

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:57.479
So that's really, really important that just a few lines using our Magritte pipe, we can

00:13:57.479 --> 00:14:01.080
do just a streamlined type of analysis.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:07.000
And then once we have the conflict, and we have our background map, we can just combine

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.599
them using the SF package.

00:14:08.599 --> 00:14:12.679
Again, it's not that difficult if you know how to use SF package.

00:14:12.679 --> 00:14:19.000
And with ggplot2, in two lines of code, two, three lines, we have our map.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.440
And this map already show a lot.

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:24.280
You see where you have more conflict and where you have less conflict.

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:27.159
And that's really what we want at the beginning.

00:14:27.159 --> 00:14:32.440
Now that we have all this, let's combine our document and see how it looks in one page.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:34.919
Well, it looks okay.

00:14:34.919 --> 00:14:39.200
And I think we can already share it, so I'm going to get the information from this.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:42.760
But we said something really key and important, right?

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:47.719
That the designer, Javier, he's the one working on a template.

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:57.119
And what we want is our product to look the same and to follow the chart policy or color

00:14:57.119 --> 00:14:58.119
or everything.

00:14:58.119 --> 00:15:01.239
I mean, the organization requires, because sometimes they say, okay, you have to use

00:15:01.239 --> 00:15:05.000
this color because that's our brand, and that's fine.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.960
So using the template that Javier shared with us, it looks totally different, and I think

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:12.440
it looks really much better.

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:16.840
The chart are really better, the color and everything.

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:21.039
And this one will be probably the one that other partners will see.

00:15:21.039 --> 00:15:26.760
And they will not notice any big change compared to what they used to do using other tools.

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:30.679
And that part, I think I want to emphasize that is really key.

00:15:30.679 --> 00:15:36.119
So here we can see the situation, and it's just something really not a realistic product,

00:15:36.119 --> 00:15:37.119
to be honest.

00:15:37.119 --> 00:15:39.840
It's just a quick example to show you how it works.

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:46.039
And in real life, we have a lot of organizations out there now using similar workflows and

00:15:46.039 --> 00:15:48.840
more and more investing to do that.

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:51.799
So in real life, reports are really more complex.

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:57.880
It can be sometimes even like 50 pages or even more.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:15:59.320
It can be just dashboard.

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:03.760
And in case I didn't talk too much about dashboard, because I think it involves also, we can also

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:06.359
shift from Power BI Tableau to Shiny.

00:16:06.359 --> 00:16:08.919
There's really a lot of things we can do.

00:16:08.919 --> 00:16:13.960
I was just focusing on reports because I think there is a lot of potential.

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:20.799
And as you can see, yeah, the flexibility of R Markdown, the fact that you can build

00:16:20.799 --> 00:16:24.679
the template you want, allow your team to be more effective.

00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:26.640
And I will stop there.

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:32.359
But just before, I just want to add that noticing just that humanitarian organizations are really

00:16:32.359 --> 00:16:37.080
increasing using R, and that's really a good thing.

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:43.280
And a good thing because R by default will push you probably to do more in terms of reproducibility

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:44.280
and transparency.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:48.840
And I think for humanitarian organizations, that's a really key aspect.

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:56.200
If behind each number, I can tell you exactly what I did, it's really important for, because

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:01.599
it brings trust between partners, but also it reduces the number of errors we can do.

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:05.719
Because you have to keep in mind that it's a life-saving information, and one error can

00:17:05.719 --> 00:17:07.160
cost a lot.

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:14.079
So pushing and using reproducibility and transparency is just more than just, oh, I want to use

00:17:14.079 --> 00:17:15.079
R to do my stuff.

00:17:15.479 --> 00:17:22.439
It's also pushing to be more accurate, do less error, and also apply changes to my reports

00:17:22.439 --> 00:17:25.160
and my own pipeline more quickly.

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:31.000
So that's really something I think we should aim, even if it's using another tool.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.319
But I think R provides these type of things more easily.

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:38.880
There's a lot of documentation already out there, so it's just easier to invest in R.

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:47.160
Talking about investment, that's the key now, because we need to maybe work with teams that

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:52.160
are already familiar with some tools and teach them how to use R, if they are willing to

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:54.079
do that and want to do that, of course.

00:17:54.079 --> 00:17:58.560
And I think many organizations are using R today and are pushing for that.

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:06.280
But we definitely need investment infrastructure, like RStudio Connect, like maybe a Shiny server

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:09.280
if they are using Shiny, but also trainings.

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:13.119
They have to be trained in the proper way to use all these tools.

00:18:13.119 --> 00:18:18.880
And I think for us, by us, I mean a humanitarian person, I think I'm lucky because I'm part

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:24.680
of this humanitarian user group that are virtual and online, called the Humanitarian R User

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:25.680
Group.

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:31.119
We are living in Skype for the moment, and it's cool because you see other people sharing

00:18:31.119 --> 00:18:34.680
what they are doing using R, and we are asking questions.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:40.599
And it's really a friendly environment, and you can see how really R is more and more

00:18:40.599 --> 00:18:45.400
used by many, many people, and that's really, really, really key.

00:18:45.400 --> 00:18:49.920
